The one thing I would add is that the &#39;layers&#39; as encountered by the 
crawler may not be the ones you are most interested in, because there 
are many link-hop paths from your seed to each URI, and which path is 
followed first by the crawler is affected by lots of factors.

For example, you might reach one URI via an &#39;LLLL&#39; path -- four 
navigational outinks in a row -- as reported in the crawl.log.

But, that doesn&#39;t mean there isn&#39;t also a shorter &#39;LL&#39; path that *could* 
have been followed. Only that for the crawler, with all of its various 
ordering tendencies and the delays it encountered, happened to discover 
the &#39;LLLL&#39; path first. (If the first &#39;L&#39; of that short &#39;LL&#39; path was on 
a slow host, or on a host that already had hours or days worth of URIs 
queued up, then by the time it is crawled, the other &#39;LLLL&#39; path has 
already finished. Thus the &#39;LL&#39; discovery path is rejected as providing 
a non-unique URI, and never enters the crawler queues/crawl.log.)

If you want a &#39;web graph&#39; of all paths (or all shortest paths) between 
URIs, that&#39;s usually calculated via a big post-crawl analysis.

- Gordon

On 1/20/12 12:04 PM, Noah Levitt wrote:
&gt; Hello Ng Zi Kai,
&gt;
&gt; You can determine the number of hops from seed by looking at the
&gt; path-from-seed, which is the 5th column in crawl.log. The number of
&gt; letters in that field is the number of hops from seed (unless it&#39;s
&gt; more than 50 hops in which case it will be abbreviated).
&gt;
&gt; It is possible to write separate crawl logs for the different numbers
&gt; of hops, but it&#39;s not simple to configure. My suggestion would be to
&gt; split the crawl log up in a postprocessing step, by examining the
&gt; path-from-seed for each crawled url.
&gt;
&gt; Noah
&gt;
